MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the purchase of convertible securities, which will ensure a return of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global transaction would be carried out on the basis of a unit price of $29, or 28% above its current exchange rate.
Morgan Stanley was down 6.79% at $23.07 each at 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to the status of a banking holding company,” said Juan Mack, CEO of the American group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which would have to allow him to diversify his activities but he passes it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street’s biggest names to behave much more cautiously than before.
The modalities presented last Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: on Monday, Morgan had announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for almost $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, explained in Tokyo, “we thought that the stake would have been composed only of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley bonds 7% below their carrying amount.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into common shares within a year if they are sold at more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at $47 or so, over a given period.
Morgan Stanley says the capital contributed by MUFG will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group declined to comment on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should show a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had greatly eased its balance since late August.
The last few weeks were tiring for the group, which saw its stock price fall by half while the cost of security against a risk of defaults on its debt took off.
This cost fell last Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the other sole “survivor” of the big Wall Street investment banks after the Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers bankruptcies and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part for Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chavez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, after the example of his colleagues and friends, he is the third to put to the vote a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted “yes” to the referendum, according to official results that referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" received 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted outside the polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organization had announced a wide-ranging “yes” victory, estimating it to be between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The “Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly”, he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who lead the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chavez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, to be held in complete calm, according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observer mission, referred to a 444-point text consolidating the " new socialism " advocated by the president.
The draft Constitution entailed increasing the State ' s power over the economy, reserving it the " development planning " of a country that lived essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to the foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the head of state, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive terms of four years each and will have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa already announced that he would use this power and would seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 people kidnapped have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault against the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
All of them looked good upon their arrival at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they were unable to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the hijackers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On 19 September, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown hijackers while enjoying an off-road safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the confines of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since gone from one zulo to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptus, in charge of the organization of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of shots occurred, and they killed half of the kidnappers, the others have fled," said this official who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they had the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"It must be acknowledged that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our secret service men, the special forces," he said without going into detail.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an SUV on board which the kidnappers were on, killing six, including the Chadian chief and detaining two.
He also stated that they were related to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity (SLA-U), an assertion immediately denied by this group.
