The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of Fortis Bank.
The States of the Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization to the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis that is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support in total with 11,2 billion euros to this financial and insurance institution that also has business in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held consultations at a higher level with the president of the European Central Bank and the head of economic competition of the European Commission.
The Fortis Bank is the first to suffer from the Eurozone crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been occurring in several waves for more than a year, therefore the decisions taken with respect to the Bank, in a sense can be considered as precedent.
According to the decision taken early on Sunday, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the Bank’s property in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a part of its business, including mainly the activities - mainly insurance - bought last year from the Dutch ABN Amr<0xC3><0xB3>.
Fortis shares began a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
Analysts agree, however, that with its 85,000 employees this bank is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
The company’s shares fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has declined by more than two-thirds.
Looking at current stock prices, the total value of the group's capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company's executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management blamed the sharp fall in Fortis shares on the insecurities of the U.S. market in connection with the approval of the $700 billion U.S. package plan.
On Monday, stocks already showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the bank.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they did not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
Among the Bank’s clients so far there has been no panic, they have not invaded the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Zorro in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when viewing drug purchase data.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which to the use of the data of the recipes in all cases binds it to the approval of the given person.
The same must be in independent hands, because if not, "we trust the henhouse to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the program of follow-up of medical prescriptions.
Insurance companies make the price of insurance and the amount of compensation dependent on the client’s health status and if they think the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Before, they sent the client to medical check-up and signed the contract with him, knowing the result of the check-up.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the disease and state of health of the customer.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a number of risks, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has hardly anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multipurpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headaches and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk-increasing factor for insurance companies while the former is not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which before acquiring the necessary information from the pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
The authorities are already forcing them to do this, although they have not received a fine for negligence until now.
Some companies have also recently developed the results of laboratory tests and by combining them with drug consumption data, they get more accurate information about the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill that gives the right to control the specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another issue that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the chickens, in spite of everything, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
Global menu of Marseille
The European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutually trade partners, this issue in addition to the other mostly global issues dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a great developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs but member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit launched yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, current EU President, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission, and Javier Solana, the main foreign policy representative, welcomed Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double their trade to more than 100 billion euros in five years.
Bearing in mind that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious objective.
Thus they legally harmonized the twenty-six existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is balance, because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among the Union's trading partners.
The summit paid attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism - all forms of the latter - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also urged, although both sides bear great responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, i.e. by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least 20 percent.
India also agrees with this, just as at next year’s climate conference a global agreement should be reached and the production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wished to hinder the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports, the deal would be for a period of 15 years.
