Steve Fossett's plane found missing a year ago
The remains of the plane of Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, have been found.
The debris has been found on a high plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the area of the Sierra Nevada of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
"The plane has been located, we have sent a squadron, and now we have the confirmation that it is the very thing that Steve Fossett was flying over on the day of his disappearance," he said in a press conference.
The commissioner said no human remains were found on or around the plane.
The 63-year-old millionaire was presumed dead in February.
The U.S. Bureau of Transportation Security (NTSB) has announced that a few hours after the sighting of the remains, a squadron of investigators has been sent to identify the device: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, again in California, not far from the edge of Nevada, some personal remains of Fossett have been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents with Fossett’s name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett’s search had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, at the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the world tour in a hot air balloon: two lonely weeks of flight.
Three years later he had made the world tour by plane and without stopovers.
Among his records, also that for having flown at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertising you don't expect
An off-the-shelf SUV with an original and well-established design with defined lines and determined angles.
It is this, in short, Glk the latest born among the "compact" all-terrain vans of the star house with which Mercedes-Benz has sought to give a window of novelty in this sector.
Proper for the content outside the traditional, will be unexpected and unconventional, the communication that will accompany the launch of the suv Glk, available in the Mercedes-Benz showrooms from October 17th.
The advertising campaign that accompanied the debut of the new car launched an unprecedented mode of communication through a 3D advertising campaign, used for the first time in Italy by a car brand.
A project with maxi-posters, articulated in three different phases, that dominated the central street of the Milanese shopping, Como Avenue, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication will begin with the presentation of the car in stereoscopic version and thanks to special glasses distributed in the avenue Como it will be possible to see the new SUV in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, looking at the images you will have the impression that the car comes out of the poster.
Subsequently, through the use of the innovative Elumina8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated at different times in all its details, to be recomposed into a single image.
Undoubtedly Mercedes with this advertising is trying to introduce something new in the stereotype of automotive communication.
Can this formula capture the interest of future buyers? we will see.
